requires: []
conflicts: []
tags:
  - required
  - localization
  - keyboard
  - default

templates/partials/070-timezone/_meta.yml

title: Timezone
order: 70
required: true
selection: one
default: us_central
description: Sets the system timezone for the installed machine.
applies_to:
  os:
    - rhel7
    - rhel8
    - rhel9
    - rhel10
  profiles:
    - minimal
    - small_disk
    - developer_workstation
options:
  - id: us_central
    file: us-central.ks.j2
    title: US Central
    description: Uses the US Central timezone. This is the normal default for Fort Worth and many AeroLIT lab environments.
    recommended: true
    risk: low
    warning: ""
  - id: us_chicago
    file: us-chicago.ks.j2
    title: America/Chicago
    description: Uses the IANA-style Chicago timezone name. Functionally similar to US Central for most installs.
    recommended: false
    risk: low
    warning: "Keep either this or US Central as the preferred option long term to avoid confusing users."
  - id: us_eastern
    file: us-eastern.ks.j2
    title: US Eastern
    description: Uses the US Eastern timezone.
    recommended: false
    risk: low
    warning: ""
  - id: us_mountain
    file: us-mountain.ks.j2
    title: US Mountain
    description: Uses the US Mountain timezone.
    recommended: false
    risk: low
    warning: ""
  - id: us_pacific
    file: us-pacific.ks.j2
    title: US Pacific
    description: Uses the US Pacific timezone.
    recommended: false
    risk: low
    warning: ""
notes: >
  Timezone is separated from language and keyboard so users can change the
  system time zone without accidentally changing the system language or keyboard layout.
requires: []
conflicts: []
tags:
  - required
  - timezone
  - localization
  - default

One small recommendation: long term, I would probably keep either us-central.ks.j2 or us-chicago.ks.j2, not both. For now it is fine to keep both while you are building this out.